hands_on_practices.solution:
For first-order recovery kinetics in FRAP, the fluorescence in the bleached region approaches its plateau as
$$
F(t)=F_{\infty}\bigl(1-\exp(-k t)\bigr).
$$
By definition of the half-time, $F(t_{1/2})=\frac{1}{2}F_{\infty}$, so
$$
F_{\infty}\bigl(1-\exp(-k t_{1/2})\bigr)=\frac{1}{2}F_{\infty}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
1-\exp(-k t_{1/2})=\frac{1}{2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\exp(-k t_{1/2})=\frac{1}{2}.
$$
Taking natural logarithms,
$$
-k t_{1/2}=\ln\!\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=-\ln 2
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
k=\frac{\ln 2}{t_{1/2}}.
$$
Therefore, the ratio of turnover rate constants is
$$
\frac{k_{\text{mitotic}}}{k_{\text{interphase}}}
=\frac{\ln 2/t_{1/2,\text{mitotic}}}{\ln 2/t_{1/2,\text{interphase}}}
=\frac{t_{1/2,\text{interphase}}}{t_{1/2,\text{mitotic}}}.
$$
Substituting the given values,
$$
\frac{k_{\text{mitotic}}}{k_{\text{interphase}}}
=\frac{153}{21.5}
=\frac{306}{43}
\approx 7.116279\ldots
$$
Rounded to three significant figures, this is $7.12$.
